        <table-wrap-foot>
          <fn id="t001fn001">
            <p>In 36 months the clinical event occurs in 13% +/- 1% of patients without intervention; and 18% +/- 1% in 48 months. Sample size calculations reflect 90% power to detect 0.8 treatment hazard ratio using two-sided hypothesis testing and α = 0.05. The cost of screening is $500/patient and the per patient trial cost is $4000 (36-month trial) or $5000 (48-month trial). <bold>Screening Threshold</bold> is the proportion of patients who will be screened out of the trial based on biomarker level. <bold>Event Rate</bold> is the estimated rate of the clinical event in the enriched study population not receiving the intervention. <bold>Sample Size</bold> is the trial sample size calculated based on the event rate and statistical testing specifications. <bold>Total Screened</bold> is the total number of patients who would need to be screened to enroll the trial, which depends on the sample size and level of enrichment (screening threshold). <bold>Total Cost</bold> summarizes patient-related costs of different levels of enrichment, specifically the cost of biomarker-based screening and the cost of having a patient in a trial. Results show the potential for the biomarker to allow substantially smaller trial sample size and cost savings, but impose a greater burden on the total number of patients to screen to enroll the trial. These results are displayed in <xref ref-type="fig" rid="pone.0239486.g001">Fig 1</xref>, which also displays standard error estimates.</p>
          </fn>
        </table-wrap-foot>
      </table-wrap>
